  "Dissociation is when an ionic compound separates into its individual ions when dissolved in water. For example, NaCl dissociates into Na+ and Cl- ions in solution.": "",
  "Table salt (NaCl) has a melting point of 801 degrees Celsius, while sugar (C12H22O11) melts at 186 degrees Celsius. What explains this large difference?": "",
  "Salt is ionic with strong ion attractions while sugar is covalent with weaker forces": "",
  "Salt has more atoms per molecule than sugar so it takes more energy to melt it": "",
  "Sugar is a metal compound while salt is a nonmetal compound making them different": "",
  "Salt is heavier than sugar so heavier substances always have higher melting points": "",
  "NaCl is an ionic compound with strong electrostatic attractions in its crystal lattice, requiring high temperatures to break apart. Sugar is a covalent compound with weaker intermolecular forces.": "",
  "A student dissolves salt in water and tests it with a light bulb conductivity tester. The light turns on. Then the student dissolves sugar in water and the light does not turn on. Why?": "",
